@node "e_Einleitung" "Einleitung"

                           Genesis 1,26

@{u}Preface@{uu}

In fact, the idea is not new, it is indeed quite old. In the stone age, the humans painted pictures of themselves in their caves. Some time later, monks painted tiny little pictures into handwritten books. One day, some wise guy invented the camera, causing thousands of painters to lose their job. Then came digital picture processing, and the basics for our program were finally established. Some three years ago, in our local Munich Network called MAx we had the idea of collecting pictures of all our users and view them while reading the corresponding mails. When recently a guy from the german Fido area AMIGA.GER started collecting JPG's of AMIGA.GER members, we finally got to work and started coding...

Out came a program called Thumbmail, showing the picture of the mails' sender, if available. OS3 Datatypes are used for this task. Currently, only Spot(reg. versions only, because of the lack of ARexx in the unreg. one) and Foozle are supported, but support for further programs will, depending on YOUR wishes an the easyness of implementation, be implemented. A huge ARexx-port a la Spot will mightily save us work with that.

The minimum hardware supported is an OCS, OS3.0 Amiga.
We recommend AGA or gfx-card for nicer images.

@endnode


@node "e_Bilder_an_uns" "WICHTIG! Bitte lesen!!!"

@{u}Sending and spreading pictures@{uu}

The organisation for spreading pictures has only just begun. First, it is important to get a huge base of pictures, which is, at the moment mostly non-existant.

Because of this, for now we are collecting all the pictures sent to @{"us" link "e_Bilder_an_uns" 0} (or Ingo Juergensmann 2:2449/413.19 of AMIGA.GER) and distribute them with ThumbMail. Later, we will only distribute the differences to the previous release (socalled Diff's) to avoid large redundant data to be sent.

We would be very lucky about another person spreading the images, e.g. using a german or even international tick-echo. This would quite save us time we could invest in updating our program.

@{b}================================================================
IMPORTANT:   Everybody  sending  pictures has to agree to a free
and  public  spreading  of those via Aminet, PD-series and other
means of communication.

Do only send pictures of yourself!  In case the the person shown
on  a  picture  does  not  agree  with public release of his/her
picture,  the  person who sent us the picture for public release
can be made liable!
NO                         FAKES,                        PLEASE!
================================================================
@{ub}


Herewith, we call you to send @{"us" link "e_Autoren" 0} a picture of @{b}YOU@{ub}, so that others get the kick watching you, too.

To ensure that all pictures are displayed on all Amigas in the same quality, we commited ourselves to the following two formats:

  IFF ILBM, 100 x 100 Pixel, 32 colors dithered

  *@{b}and@{ub}*

  IFF ILBM, 100 x 100 Pixel, 4 colors grayscale dithered

You will save us a huge part of our work if you send your pictures in these formats. We'll take other picture too, and convert them to the right format, but then you won't have any influence on the quality of the conversion ;-)

It is possible, though, to use images in any resolution and depth (well, up to 256 colours) and in any file format that is recognized by a working datatype.

Our filename definition is as follows:

Picname.<some number>.<number of colors><c/g>
                                          | |
                                          | l grayscale
                                          |
                                          l colors

e.g. "Curt Cobain.1.32c"
(also see included pictures)

Send your pictures e.g. UUencoded to:
@{"Christian Buchner" link "e_Autoren" 0}, Fidonet 2:2480/465
EMAIL: flowerp@eikon.e-technik.tu-muenchen.de.

The snail mail address is available @{"here" link "e_Autoren" 0}.

@endnode


@node "e_Inst" "Installation"

@{u}How to install@{uu}

The installation is done quite userfriendly via the Commodore-Installer®. The least amiga supported is one running OS3.

The main program is copied to "SYS:WBStartup" and is started on every bootup. It quietly waits in the background for any supported mailer. The installer script also allows to install the included picture database, both 4 grayscales and/or 32 colors. The assign for the picture-drawer will then be added to you user-startup. Furthermore, the screennotify.library will be extracted and copied to LIBS:. Ready.

As neither Spot nor Foozle are able to open a screen containing more than 8 or 4 colors, respectively, we suggest to use a screen-promotor, preferably NewMode, which is available on the Aminet (util/cdity).

@endnode


@node "e_Bedienung" "Usage"

@{u}The usage of ThumbMail is quite easy.@{uu}

It will be started at bootup and stay in the background until a mail is displayed.  Then, in the bottom right corner, a tiny window is opened containing a picture of the mail's sender, if available.  This window can be moved anywhere on the screen.  The window can be resized as well, using an invisible sizing gadget. The image in the window will be resized automatically to fit the window dimensions.

The program has got a commodity interface and a user interface using MUI 2.3 or later.  Using this, you can save your settings, window positions, hotkeys etc.  Using the activation hotkey, you can disable the program temporarily.  It will close its windows and stay quiet.  Now you can also change the path where your pictures are located.  It is no longer fixed to "ThumbMail:" as in earlier versions of the program.

ThumbMail can be quitted at any time by sending a CTRL-C.

@endnode


@node "e_Bild-Datenbank" "Picture database"

@{u}Structure and syntax of the picture database@{uu}

All pictures are located in a directory. Usually this directory is pointed to by the assign "ThumbMail:". You may freely specify the path, however. Normally this work is done by the installer script.

A new option is that you now can sort your images into subdirectories. So you can separate the images for different networks (e.g. FidoNet, AmigaNet, UUCP).

The pictures must be named exactly like the senders of the mail.

Example "Curt Cobain"

Further data may optionally appear in the filename. This data must be separated from the name by a period.

Beispiel: "Curt Cobain.1.32c"

The specifications after the first period will be ignored by the program. We use them to specify the picture count and the number of colors in the picture. The c marks a color image, the g is used for grayscale images. This way it is easier to distinguish between the images.

Any picture (data) format that will be recognized by the datatypes of WB3.0, may be used. Images with a resolution other than defined by ThumbMail's window size will be scaled to the correct size. However, it is not advisable at all to archive the images in a high resolution because the scaling requires quite a lot of computing power. The usage of JPG images is therefore not recommended as well.

There may exist more than one image of a person. The program then chooses randomly from the diversion of pictures. This results in more variety in the boring everyday-net.

In case you wish one picture to appear more often than others, you can assign a higher priority to it. This is done by specifying "Pri: <Number>" in the file comment (filenote). If this is ommitted, priority 1 is assumed.

Example for the command setting the file comment:

Filenote "Curt Cobain.1.32c" "Pri: 5"

We plan to allow further data in the filenote, e.g. the specification of DOS-patterns to make a picture appear only in certain message areas or to make the output dependent of the message subject (see -> @{"ToDo" link "e_ToDo" 0}).

@endnode


